---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "datePublished": "2026-07-13",
  "dateModified": "2026-07-13",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How does overclocking affect CPU and GPU power consumption?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Overclocking increases power consumption exponentially. Because power draw scales linearly with frequency but quadratically with voltage, increasing the voltage by 10% can increase power draw by over 30%."
      }
    }
  ]
};
---

<Layout
  title="Overclocking Power Consumption: Voltage & Load Sizing — PSUCheck"
  description="Learn how manual overclocking, PBO, and Intel Turbo profiles affect system power draw. Understand how to size your PSU for heavy overvolts."
  schema={faqSchema}
>
  <article class="guide-article">
    <div class="container">
      <header class="guide-header">
        <div class="guide-meta">
          <span class="badge badge-safe">✓ E-E-A-T Verified</span>
          <span>Updated: July 13, 2026</span>
        </div>
        <h1>Overclocking &amp; Power Sizing Constraints</h1>
        <p class="guide-lead">
          Pushing clocks requires extra power. This guide explains how overclocking, overvolting,
          and load line profiles affect system wattage sizing.
        </p>
      </header>

      <div class="guide-layout">
        <main class="guide-content" id="main-content">
          <h2>The Mathematics of Overvolting</h2>
          <p>
            The general formula for CMOS component dynamic power draw is:
          </p>
          <p style="font-family:monospace;font-size:1.125rem;text-align:center;color:var(--color-accent-cyan);">
            Power ∝ Capacitance × Frequency × Voltage²
          </p>
          <p>
            Because voltage is squared, even tiny increases in core voltage (Vcore) lead to exponential climbs
            in heat output and power consumption. A CPU drawing 120W at stock settings can easily exceed 220W+
            with a modest 0.15V overvolt.
          </p>

          <h2>Motherboard VRM and Transient Peaks</h2>
          <p>
            Overclocked components draw larger, more violent transient current spikes. A manual GPU overclock
            can bypass default power limit restrictions, causing the card to draw up to 220% of its rated power
            during extreme load spikes.
          </p>
          <div class="important-warning">
            <strong>⚠ PSU Buffer Rule:</strong> If you plan to manually overclock your CPU and GPU, add a minimum
            of 150W to 200W of additional safety headroom to your recommended PSU calculation.
          </div>

          <h2>Safe Power Management (Undervolting)</h2>
          <p>
            Modern enthusiasts prefer <strong>undervolting</strong>: reducing core voltage offsets while maintaining
            stock frequencies. This reduces heat, saves up to 50W of power, and stabilizes frame times.
          </p>

          <div style="margin-top:3rem;">
            <a href="/psu-calculator" class="btn btn-primary">Check system overheads</a>
          </div>
        </main>

        <aside class="guide-sidebar">
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Calculators</h3>
            <ul style="list-style:none;padding:0;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.5rem;font-size:0.875rem;">
              <li><a href="/psu-calculator">⚡ PSU Calculator</a></li>
              <li><a href="/pc-builder">🖥️ PC Build Cost Calculator</a></li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Other Guides</h3>
            <ul style="list-style:none;padding:0;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.5rem;font-size:0.875rem;">
              <li><a href="/guides/pc-bottleneck-guide">Bottleneck Guide</a></li>
              <li><a href="/guides/psu-sizing-guide">PSU Sizing Guide</a></li>
              <li><a href="/guides/aio-cooler-power-draw">AIO Cooler Power</a></li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </aside>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
</Layout>

<style>
.guide-article { padding: 4rem 0; }
.guide-header { margin-bottom: 3rem; }
.guide-meta { display:flex; gap: 1rem; align-items:center; font-size: 0.8125rem; color: var(--text-tertiary); margin-bottom: 0.75rem; }
.guide-lead { font-size: 1.15rem; color: var(--text-secondary); max-width: 65ch; line-height: 1.65; margin-top: 0.5rem; }
.guide-layout { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr; gap: 3rem; }
@media (min-width: 1024px) {
  .guide-layout { grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 8fr) minmax(0, 4fr); }
}
.guide-content h2 { margin-top: 2.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
.guide-content p, .guide-content li { color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.75; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
.guide-content ul { padding-left: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
.important-warning { background: var(--color-surface-raised); border-left: 4px solid var(--color-accent-orange); padding: 1rem; border-radius: var(--radius-md); margin-top: 1rem; color: var(--text-secondary); }
.guide-sidebar { display:flex; flex-direction:column; gap: 1.5rem; }
.guide-sidebar .card { padding: 1.25rem; }
</style>
